[00:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Many years ago, I was one of the first to start reviewing PC devices on this channel. Whether it be Global PTT and Real PTT handsets or Zello network radios, the problem with them was always the price. They were expensive, much'

[00:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'more expensive than conventional two-way VHF and UHF radios. And while they work well and of course offer near global coverage, and there were some funky designs, I always found the setup a bit of a headache. Banggood reach out to me'

[00:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'from time to time to see if I\'ll review their products. From time to time, I say yes if it works as it should and think you\'ll be interested in that particular product. So today we\'re looking at the POC AT1 from Bofang under the Alvitez'

[00:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'name. I\'m not quite sure how to pronounce that word. The name Alvitez apparently combines the words alert, elite, and the French word vite meaning fast. I\'ve said before I don\'t like'

[00:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'doing product reviews. I don\'t particularly enjoy them, but if the product is good, I don\'t mind too much. This is really good, and you can get a pair with a preloaded SIM card ready to work out of the box for a little over'

[01:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '£60, meaning you can talk to someone in the next room or on the next continent in real time like a normal two-way radio for £30 a piece without any messing around. Before we get started, if you want to take a look at them, I\'ll leave'

[01:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'a link in the description below. When I\'ve reviewed things like this in the past, I get jumped on by people saying, "It\'s not real radio. It\'s just a mobile phone. It\'s useless without the cellular networks." So, let me start by'

[01:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'saying that\'s completely true. A package like this has its advantages, though. It\'s encrypted and can\'t be picked up on a scanner or eaves dropped up on. Therefore, it\'s completely private. They work in dozens of countries, so offer'

[01:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'near global coverage. You can literally talk to somebody thousands of miles away. And yes, they do rely on the mobile phone networks, so in an outage, they won\'t work. They operate over 4G LTE and so can outperform a standard VHF'

[01:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and UHF 2-way radio in terms of range. These devices don\'t need to be in line of sight with each other. The big question I\'m sure you\'re all asking is, what about the SIM card?'

[02:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Well, they come with a preloaded SIM card and an included data plan. With previous devices I\'ve reviewed, the plans were expensive. The included plan with these lasts for 3 years, after which you simply provide Bofang with'

[02:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'your SIM card ID and they\'ll handle the renewal for you. It\'s good for up to 160 hours of voice usage per month with 800 megabytes of data and there\'s no extra or hidden fees. I\'ve never seen a PC deal as easy and convenient as this.'

[02:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'In the box, you get the radio. It has a small 1.7 in screen and a300 millia battery which gives 72 hours of standby. It\'s fully USB rechargeable, too. It\'s'

[02:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'light at just 120 g and supports a 3.5 mm earpiece which isn\'t supplied. The large speaker gives you decent audio quality, too. You also get a USB charging cable, a belt clip, and a wrist'

[03:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'strap. Setup is really simple. You get a QR code in the box for the Android or iOS app and manual. There is a paper manual in the box, too. You can easily bind and manage devices,'

[03:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'create or join groups, and track online members in real time. Your phone acts as an extra device, which allows you to communicate with the PC radios. You can replay the message history any time and also turn recording and logging off.'

[03:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'They support group, private, and temporary calls, allowing you to start instant one-to-one or one to many PTT calls without changing group settings. Once a temporary call ends, the system returns to your original group, so'

[03:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'communication in your original group stays smooth and uninterrupted. There\'s also an SOS feature and location features, which can be turned off. Let me quickly show you the out ofthe-box setup. First, turn on the radios. The'

[03:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'SIM cards are already installed. Then you need to go to about and load up the IMEI number. In the app, register your free account and sign in. Then select bind device and scan the IMEI on the'

[04:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'radio screen. All I then did was change the radio\'s name. Next, you can create a group. Press create group, change its name, and then have the devices you\'d like in'

[04:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that particular group. The radios will automatically enter that group when you switch them on, and you can select your desired group in the radio. You don\'t need to do anything else. Your radios will now work back to back as soon as'

[04:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you switch them on. I\'ll show you some other bits, though. You can view your group member list. You can make a temporary call to another member. You can invite other local members'

[04:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'or exit the group you\'re in. You can view your groups, create a new group, or join a new group. You can also set things like backlight and power settings,'

[04:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'tone, and mic gain. And that\'s it. It\'s so easy. Now, let\'s test the audio. These radios sound good, and the audio is clear and'

[05:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'punchy. Don\'t forget, you\'re hearing it via my microphone and your speakers. This is a test of the Bofang Alvitez POC AT1. Testing from the iPhone on the app.'

